image.altText: Wine and cheese platter

props.synopsis: Ever tried shipping something between Tasmania and the mainland? The hefty cost is supposed to be equal to driving goods down a highway, but the 'clunky' old federal scheme designed to ensure that hasn't been working for a while.

title.children: Call to fix Tasmania's 'highway' to help lower cost of state's produce

image.altText: Right side profile of a female tuba player.

props.synopsis: As a kid, Rachel Kelly saw "all the other girls play the flute" but after battling to make a decent sound on that, turned to the tuba — and now is doing what no other woman has done before.

title.children: Rachel may not be one to blow her own horn, but others happy to celebrate orchestra's milestone

image.altText: Spirit of Tasmania IV ship in port.

props.synopsis: Tasmania's government has paid for double-page ads across three newspapers to address "frequently asked questions" about why the Spirit of Tasmania ferries are still a long way off operating — with Labor saying the ads are a "blatant waste" of money.

title.children: 'Blatant waste': Critics lash double-page ads explaining ferry debacle

image.altText: Protesters at an anti-salmon farming rally on a beach.

props.synopsis: A Coalition government would not ban salmon farming in Tasmania's Macquarie Harbour even if the Maugean skate's threatened species' status is upgraded to "critically endangered", Peter Dutton says, as people take to the water in protest at the industry.

title.children: Dutton backs salmon farming even if threatened species status worsens

image.altText: Macaque monkeys.

props.synopsis: A visit to the 'monkey park' has been a part of this Tasmanian city's appeal since the late 1800s, so what is the history of Launceston's Monkey Island? And does it have a future?

title.children: How Launceston got its monkeys — and why they could be gone within decades

image.altText: A sepia photograph of Amy Sherwin, who is side on to the camera, in 1887

props.synopsis: Known as the "Tasmanian nightingale", Amy Sherwin was Australia's first international opera singer. Today, she is relatively unknown, but there is a push to change that.

title.children: Australia's first big opera star sang for kings and died penniless

image.altText: Bauble in a celery top pine tree.

props.synopsis: A tree is central to many Christmas celebrations, but it doesn't have to be a one-hit-wonder dragged from storage each year or even one that is cut and then recycled after use. A botanist shares her tips on using potted native species.

title.children: Did you miss? 📣 Native species that fit the bill for a perfect Christmas tree alternative

image.altText: A toddler is crying amid piles of debris in the aftermath of Cyclone Tracy in Darwin.

props.synopsis: Fifty years ago, Cyclone Tracy changed the lives of those who lived through it. But it has also fundamentally changed the rule book to building in Australia.

title.children: Cyclone Tracy destroyed Darwin and nails are partly to blame

image.altText: A woman with grey hair.

props.synopsis: Federal Financial Services Minister Stephen Jones says state consumer ministers will meet this week discuss ways to stamp out poor behaviour by retirement village operators.

title.children: Ministers meet to tackle 'cunningly designed rip-offs'

image.altText: Bradfield residents Scott and Joann Lutiger stand at the fence of their property looking at the camera

props.synopsis: Residents sitting on a parcel of land that will host a transport corridor to the new Western Sydney Airport have slammed the government's acquisition offer for their property.

title.children: Western Sydney residents slam 'disgusting' airport land offer

image.altText: Nuclear power station chimneys

props.synopsis: After heavy criticism, Australia's leading science agency doubles down its findings that the cost of nuclear power for Australia would likely be double that of renewable energy, and it would take at least 15 years for a plant to be built.

title.children: New CSIRO report doubles down on nuclear price and time frames

image.altText: A person wearing a hoodie and medical mask peering through the window from the back seat of a taxi.

image.altText: Two trains at a train station.

image.altText: An overhead shot of three kids reading a book

image.altText: Taylor Swift smiles and waves on stage in a purple tinsel jacket and a blue sparkling bodysuit

props.synopsis: It's been a long time coming, but Taylor Swift's Eras Tour is about to end. As the dust (and glitter) begins to settle, these numbers show how it became one of the biggest concert tours of all time.

image.altText: Young woman in jeans and black tee holding a camera, standing in a park

image.altText: ABC News Breakfast - James Glenday & Bridget Brennan

title.children: James Glenday to replace Michael Rowland as News Breakfast co-host in 2025

image.altText: An outback road sign that has the word "disgraceful" written in texta between the words "rough surface".

image.altText: A crowd of people walking along a street in a central business district in Melbourne on a sunny day.

image.altText: Man standing with luxury car inside penthouse
